<!-- ═══════ MAIN CONTENT + SIDEBAR ═══════ -->
<section class="page-main">
  <div class="page-main-grid">

    <div class="page-content">

      <!-- Overview -->
      <div class="content-section">
        <div class="content-label">Overview</div>
        <h2 class="content-h2">What Does Home <em>Physiotherapy Consist Of?</em></h2>
        <p class="content-p">
          Home physiotherapy consists of a comprehensive set of electrotherapy modalities and hands-on rehabilitation techniques delivered directly at your doorstep. The service includes <strong>Shortwave Diathermy, Ultrasonic Therapy, Hot Pads, Infrared Therapy, and Laser Therapy</strong> — all brought to your home using portable, professional-grade equipment.
        </p>
        <p class="content-p">
          In addition to these electrotherapy modalities, home physiotherapy includes <strong>mobilisation techniques</strong> — comprising both active and passive exercises — designed to restore movement, build strength, and prevent complications such as joint contractures. Each session is personalised to your specific condition, ensuring consistent progress and faster recovery in the comfort of your own home.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Electrotherapy Modalities -->
      <div class="content-section">
        <div class="content-label">Electrotherapy Modalities</div>
        <h2 class="content-h2">Advanced <em>Therapy Equipment</em> We Bring to You</h2>
        <p class="content-p">Our physiotherapists carry portable, professional-grade equipment to every home visit — the same modalities used in leading physiotherapy clinics.</p>

        <div class="modality-cards">

          <div class="modality-card swd">
            <div class="modality-card-num">01</div>
            <div class="modality-card-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-wave-square"></i></div>
            <h4>Shortwave Diathermy (SWD)</h4>
            <p>Shortwave Diathermy uses high-frequency electromagnetic energy to generate <strong>deep heat within muscles and joints</strong> — reducing pain, relieving stiffness, and improving circulation. It is particularly effective for arthritis, chronic joint pain, and muscle spasms where deep tissue heating is required to promote healing and restore function.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="modality-card us">
            <div class="modality-card-num">02</div>
            <div class="modality-card-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-circle-nodes"></i></div>
            <h4>Ultrasonic Therapy</h4>
            <p>Ultrasonic Therapy uses high-frequency sound waves that penetrate deep into soft tissue to <strong>stimulate cellular repair, reduce inflammation, and break down scar tissue</strong>. It is commonly used for tendon injuries, ligament sprains, muscle tears, and post-surgical tissue healing — promoting faster recovery at the cellular level.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="modality-card ir">
            <div class="modality-card-num">03</div>
            <div class="modality-card-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-sun"></i></div>
            <h4>Infrared Therapy & Hot Pads</h4>
            <p>Infrared Therapy and Hot Pads provide <strong>targeted superficial heat therapy</strong> to relax tight muscles, reduce muscle spasm, and improve local blood flow. Both are used as preparation before manual therapy and exercise sessions — increasing tissue flexibility and reducing pain perception to make mobilisation more effective.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="modality-card laser">
            <div class="modality-card-num">04</div>
            <div class="modality-card-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-bolt"></i></div>
            <h4>Laser Therapy (LLLT)</h4>
            <p>Low-Level Laser Therapy (LLLT) uses specific wavelengths of light to <strong>reduce pain and inflammation</strong> at the tissue level — stimulating mitochondrial activity and accelerating the healing process. It is effective for nerve pain, soft tissue injuries, wound healing, and chronic musculoskeletal conditions.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="modality-card mob">
            <div class="modality-card-num">05</div>
            <div class="modality-card-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-hands"></i></div>
            <h4>Mobilisation Techniques</h4>
            <p>Mobilisation includes both <strong>active and passive exercises</strong> to restore range of motion, reduce stiffness, and improve movement quality. Passive mobilisation is performed by the therapist for patients who cannot move independently, while active exercises are guided movements performed by the patient to progressively rebuild strength and function.</p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Rehabilitation -->
      <div class="content-section">
        <div class="content-label">Rehabilitation Programmes</div>
        <h2 class="content-h2">Who Benefits from <em>Home Rehabilitation?</em></h2>
        <p class="content-p">Home rehabilitation is designed for patients who require regular, consistent physiotherapy but cannot travel to a clinic — whether due to their condition, post-surgical restrictions, or preference.</p>

        <div class="rehab-grid">

          <div class="rehab-card">
            <div class="rehab-card-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-brain"></i></div>
            <h4>Neurological Rehabilitation</h4>
            <p>Patients with paraparesis (partial leg weakness) and paraplegia require specialised strengthening and movement programmes to maximise functional recovery. Home rehab prevents joint contractures, maintains muscle tone, and progressively improves strength and independence.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="rehab-card">
            <div class="rehab-card-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-bone"></i></div>
            <h4>Post-Surgical Rehabilitation</h4>
            <p>After fracture surgery, joint replacement, or any orthopaedic surgical intervention — a structured home rehabilitation programme restores mobility, prevents joint stiffness, and builds strength through active and passive exercise protocols tailored to the surgical procedure.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="rehab-card">
            <div class="rehab-card-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-arrows-to-dot"></i></div>
            <h4>Degenerative Condition Management</h4>
            <p>Patients with osteoarthritis, disc degeneration, or chronic joint conditions benefit from home exercise programmes that maintain joint mobility, strengthen supporting muscles, and prevent functional decline — reducing dependence on medication and delaying surgical intervention.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="rehab-card">
            <div class="rehab-card-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-person-walking"></i></div>
            <h4>Contracture Prevention & Mobility</h4>
            <p>Bedridden or mobility-limited patients are at high risk of developing joint contractures — permanent stiffening that severely limits movement. Regular passive mobilisation and positioning programmes at home prevent contracture formation and preserve existing range of motion.</p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Exercise Types -->
      <div class="content-section">
        <div class="content-label">Mobilisation Exercises</div>
        <h2 class="content-h2">Active & Passive <em>Exercise Protocols</em></h2>
        <div class="check-list">
          <div class="check-item">
            <i class="fa-solid fa-circle-check"></i>
            <span><strong>Active exercises</strong> — performed independently by the patient to build strength, coordination, and functional movement under therapist supervision</span>
          </div>
          <div class="check-item">
            <i class="fa-solid fa-circle-check"></i>
            <span><strong>Passive mobilisation</strong> — performed by the therapist to maintain joint range of motion in patients who cannot move independently</span>
          </div>
          <div class="check-item">
            <i class="fa-solid fa-circle-check"></i>
            <span><strong>Active-assisted exercises</strong> — therapist supports the patient's movement to progressively restore function</span>
          </div>
          <div class="check-item">
            <i class="fa-solid fa-circle-check"></i>
            <span><strong>Strengthening exercises</strong> — targeted muscle strengthening for paraparesis, post-surgical weakness, and degenerative conditions</span>
          </div>
          <div class="check-item">
            <i class="fa-solid fa-circle-check"></i>
            <span><strong>Stretching & flexibility</strong> — prevent contractures, improve tissue extensibility, and restore normal joint mechanics</span>
          </div>
          <div class="check-item">
            <i class="fa-solid fa-circle-check"></i>
            <span><strong>Balance & proprioception</strong> — restore joint position sense and stability after injury or surgery</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Who this is for -->
      <div class="content-section">
        <div class="content-label">Ideal Candidates</div>
        <h2 class="content-h2">Is Home Physiotherapy <em>Right for You?</em></h2>
        <div class="check-list">
          <div class="check-item"><i class="fa-solid fa-circle-check"></i><span>Patients <strong>recovering from fracture surgery</strong> or orthopaedic procedures who cannot travel to a clinic</span></div>
          <div class="check-item"><i class="fa-solid fa-circle-check"></i><span>Individuals with <strong>paraparesis or paraplegia</strong> requiring neurological strengthening and mobility programmes</span></div>
          <div class="check-item"><i class="fa-solid fa-circle-check"></i><span>Elderly patients with <strong>arthritis or degenerative conditions</strong> who find clinic travel difficult</span></div>
          <div class="check-item"><i class="fa-solid fa-circle-check"></i><span>Post-surgical patients needing <strong>daily physiotherapy</strong> during the initial recovery phase</span></div>
          <div class="check-item"><i class="fa-solid fa-circle-check"></i><span>Patients at risk of <strong>joint contractures</strong> due to prolonged immobility or neurological conditions</span></div>
          <div class="check-item"><i class="fa-solid fa-circle-check"></i><span>Anyone who prefers the <strong>convenience and consistency</strong> of professional physiotherapy at home</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

